            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Ive been trying to separate files from different projects is by using tabs and changing the tab working directory to point to the root of each project, but this has the problem that buffers in vim/nvim are not scoped in any way.\r\n\r\nTabs are indeed the current best answer. It's true that there is no other \"scoping\" concept which would \"contain\" navigation. But also, Nvim is fast to startup, and a \"peer to peer\" concept https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/1180 would be an alternative that implicitly and fully \"scopes\" everything by virtue of being in a separate process, while allowing peer Nvims to communicate with each other in an opt-in manner.\r\n\r\nSo the question is which of these (\"multi-tenant\" vs \"peer to peer\") is more tractable/extensible/intuitive/maintainable. Historically, we have moved away from multi-tenancy, in favor of composability.\r\n\r\nNote also that for \"multi project\", we have a proposal outlined here: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/8610#issuecomment-1367994885 . It doesn't address \"scoped navigation\", but then neither does any other IDE/editor (again, that's multi-tenancy, aka \"inner platforms all the way down\").",
